.RE
.B
\fBalive_common_option() ::\fR
\fB          {alive,\fR
\fB           #{count_max := CountMax :: pos_integer(),\fR
\fB             interval := Interval :: timeout()}}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
This option is used to configure the alive messages. Alive messages are sent through the encrypted channel and are typically used to detect that a connection became unresponsive.

.PP
\fIcount_max\fR sets the maximum number of alive messages which may be sent without receiving any messages back from the peer. If this threshold is reached the connection will be terminated. \fIinterval\fR sets a timeout interval, in milliseconds, after which, if no data has been received from the peer, a message to request a response from the peer is sent.

.PP
The default is \fI#{count_max => 3, interval => infinity}\fR, which means that alive messages will not be sent to the peer, since the \fIinterval\fR is set to \fIinfinity\fR.

.PP
No alive messages are sent during renegotiation, however, a timeout derived from the alive parameters is set to ensure that unresponsive connections are terminated.


.RE
.B
\fBauth_methods_common_option() :: {auth_methods, string()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Comma-separated string that determines which authentication methods that the client shall support and in which order they are tried. Defaults to \fI"publickey,keyboard-interactive,password"\fR

.PP
Note that the client is free to use any order and to exclude methods.


.RE
.B
\fBauthentication_client_options() ::\fR
\fB          {user, string()} | {password, string()}.\fR

.br
.RS
user
.RS 2
Provides the username. If this option is not given, 
\fIssh\fR reads from the environment (\fILOGNAME\fR or \fIUSER\fR on UNIX, \fIUSERNAME\fR on Windows).

.RE

password
.RS 2
Provides a password for password authentication. If this option is not given, the user is asked for a password, if the password authentication method is attempted.


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBauthentication_daemon_options() ::\fR
\fB          ssh_file:system_dir_daemon_option() |\fR
\fB          {auth_method_kb_interactive_data, prompt_texts()} |\fR
\fB          {user_passwords, [{UserName :: string(), Pwd :: string()}]} |\fR
\fB          {pk_check_user, boolean()} |\fR
\fB          {password, string()} |\fR
\fB          {pwdfun, pwdfun_2() | pwdfun_4()} |\fR
\fB          {no_auth_needed, boolean()}.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBcallbacks_daemon_options() ::\fR
\fB          {failfun,\fR
\fB           fun((User :: string(),\fR
\fB                Peer :: {inet:ip_address(), inet:port_number()},\fR
\fB                Reason :: term()) ->\fR
\fB                   _)} |\fR
\fB          {connectfun,\fR
\fB           fun((User :: string(),\fR
\fB                Peer :: {inet:ip_address(), inet:port_number()},\fR
\fB                Method :: string()) ->\fR
\fB                   _)} |\fR
\fB          {bannerfun, fun((User :: string()) -> binary())}.\fR

.br
.RS
connectfun
.RS 2
Provides a fun to implement your own logging when a user authenticates to the server.


.RE

failfun
.RS 2
Provides a fun to implement your own logging when a user fails to authenticate.


.RE

bannerfun
.RS 2
Provides a fun to implement the construction of a banner text that is sent at the beginning of the user authentication. The banner will not be sent if the function does not return a binary.


