\fBprotocol_version() ::\fR
\fB          {Major :: pos_integer(), Minor :: non_neg_integer()}.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBpubkey_alg() ::\fR
\fB          'ecdsa-sha2-nistp256' | 'ecdsa-sha2-nistp384' |\fR
\fB          'ecdsa-sha2-nistp521' | 'ssh-ed25519' | 'ssh-ed448' |\fR
\fB          'rsa-sha2-256' | 'rsa-sha2-512' |\fR
\fB          legacy_pubkey_alg().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBpwdfun_2() ::\fR
\fB          fun((User :: string(), Password :: string() | pubkey) ->\fR
\fB                  boolean()).\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBpwdfun_4() ::\fR
\fB          fun((User :: string(),\fR
\fB               Password :: string() | pubkey,\fR
\fB               PeerAddress :: ip_port(),\fR
\fB               State :: any()) ->\fR
\fB                  boolean() |\fR
\fB                  disconnect |\fR
\fB                  {boolean(), NewState :: any()}).\fR

.br
.RS
auth_method_kb_interactive_data
.RS 2
Sets the text strings that the daemon sends to the client for presentation to the user when using 
\fIkeyboard-interactive\fR authentication.
.PP
If the fun/3 or fun/4 is used, it is called when the actual authentication occurs and may therefore return dynamic data like time, remote ip etc.

.PP
The parameter \fIEcho\fR guides the client about need to hide the password.

.PP
The default value is: \fI{auth_method_kb_interactive_data, {"SSH server", "Enter password for \\""++User++"\\"", "password: ", false}>\fR


.RE

user_passwords
.RS 2
Provides passwords for password authentication. The passwords are used when someone tries to connect to the server and public key user-authentication fails. The option provides a list of valid usernames and the corresponding passwords.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRNote that this is very insecure due to the plain-text passwords; it is intended for test purposes. Use the \fIpwdfun\fR option to handle the password checking instead.



.RE

pk_check_user
.RS 2
Enables checking of the client's user name in the server when doing public key authentication. It is disabled by default.

.PP
The term "user" is used differently in OpenSSH and SSH in Erlang/OTP: see more in the User's Guide.

.PP
If the option is enabled, and no \fIpwdfun\fR is present, the user name must present in the user_passwords for the check to succeed but the value of the password is not checked.

.PP
In case of a \fIpwdfun\fR checking the user, the atom \fIpubkey\fR is put in the password argument.


.RE

password
.RS 2
Provides a global password that authenticates any user.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRIntended to facilitate testing. From a security perspective this option makes the server very vulnerable.



.RE

pwdfun with pwdfun_4/0
.RS 2
Provides a function for password validation. This could used for calling an external system or handling passwords stored as hash values.

.PP
This fun can also be used to make delays in authentication tries for example by calling \fItimer:sleep/1\fR.

.PP
To facilitate for instance counting of failed tries, the \fIState\fR variable could be used. This state is per connection only. The first time the pwdfun is called for a connection, the \fIState\fR variable has the value \fIundefined\fR.

.PP
The fun should return:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fItrue\fR if the user and password is valid

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIfalse\fR if the user or password is invalid

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIdisconnect\fR if a SSH_MSG_DISCONNECT message should be sent immediately. It will be followed by a close of the underlying tcp connection.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{true, NewState:any()}\fR if the user and password is valid

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{false, NewState:any()}\fR if the user or password is invalid

.RE

.PP
A third usage is to block login attempts from a missbehaving peer. The \fIState\fR described above can be used for this. The return value \fIdisconnect\fR is useful for this.

.PP
In case of the \fIpk_check_user\fR is set, the atom \fIpubkey\fR is put in the password argument when validating a public key login. The pwdfun is then responsible to check that the user name is valid.


.RE

pwdfun with pwdfun_2/0
.RS 2
Provides a function for password validation. This function is called with user and password as strings, and returns:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fItrue\fR if the user and password is valid

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIfalse\fR if the user or password is invalid

.RE

.PP
In case of the \fIpk_check_user\fR is set, the atom \fIpubkey\fR is put in the password argument when validating a public key login. The pwdfun is then responsible to check that the user name is valid.

.PP
This variant is kept for compatibility.


.RE

no_auth_needed
.RS 2
If 
\fItrue\fR, a client is authenticated without any need of providing any password or key.
.PP
This option is only intended for very special applications due to the high risk of accepting any connecting client.

.PP
The default value is \fIfalse\fR.


.RE


