.RE
.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBclose(ConnectionRef) -> ok | {error, term()}\fR
\fB               when ConnectionRef :: connection_ref().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Closes an SSH connection.


.RE
.B
\fBconnect(Host, Port, Options, NegotiationTimeout) ->\fR
\fB                 {ok, connection_ref()} | {error, term()}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Host :: host(),\fR
\fB                     Port :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                     Options :: client_options(),\fR
\fB                     NegotiationTimeout :: timeout().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Connects to an SSH server at the \fIHost\fR on \fIPort\fR.

.PP
As an alternative, an already open TCP socket could be passed to the function in \fITcpSocket\fR. The SSH initiation and negotiation will be initiated on that one with the SSH that should be at the other end.

.PP
No channel is started. This is done by calling ssh_connection:session_channel/2,4.

.PP
The \fINegotiationTimeout\fR is in milli-seconds. The default value is \fIinfinity\fR or the value of the \fIconnect_timeout\fR option, if present. For connection timeout, use the option \fIconnect_timeout\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBconnection_info(ConnectionRef, ItemList | Item) ->\fR
\fB                         InfoTupleList | InfoTuple | {error, term()}\fR
\fB                         when\fR
\fB                             ConnectionRef :: connection_ref(),\fR
\fB                             ItemList :: [Item],\fR
\fB                             Item ::\fR
\fB                                 client_version | server_version |\fR
\fB                                 user | peer | sockname | options |\fR
\fB                                 algorithms | sockname,\fR
\fB                             InfoTupleList :: [InfoTuple],\fR
\fB                             InfoTuple :: connection_info_tuple().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns information about a connection intended for e.g debugging or logging.

.PP
When the \fIKey\fR is a single \fIItem\fR, the result is a single \fIInfoTuple\fR


.RE
.B
\fBdaemon(any | inet:ip_address(),\fR
\fB             inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB             daemon_options()) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, daemon_ref()} | {error, term()};\fR
\fB            (socket, open_socket(), daemon_options()) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, daemon_ref()} | {error, term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Starts a server listening for SSH connections on the given port. If the \fIPort\fR is 0, a random free port is selected. See \fIdaemon_info/1\fR about how to find the selected port number.

.PP
As an alternative, an already open TCP socket could be passed to the function in \fITcpSocket\fR. The SSH initiation and negotiation will be initiated on that one when an SSH starts at the other end of the TCP socket.

.PP
For a description of the options, see Daemon Options.

.PP
Please note that by historical reasons both the \fIHostAddress\fR argument and the gen_tcp connect_option() \fI{ip,Address}\fR set the listening address. This is a source of possible inconsistent settings.

.PP
The rules for handling the two address passing options are:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
if \fIHostAddress\fR is an IP-address, that IP-address is the listening address. An 'ip'-option will be discarded if present.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
if \fIHostAddress\fR is the atom \fIloopback\fR, the listening address is \fIloopback\fR and an loopback address will be chosen by the underlying layers. An 'ip'-option will be discarded if present.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
if \fIHostAddress\fR is the atom \fIany\fR and no 'ip'-option is present, the listening address is \fIany\fR and the socket will listen to all addresses

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
if \fIHostAddress\fR is \fIany\fR and an 'ip'-option is present, the listening address is set to the value of the 'ip'-option

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBdaemon_info(DaemonRef, ItemList | Item) ->\fR
\fB                     InfoTupleList | InfoTuple | {error, bad_daemon_ref}\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         DaemonRef :: daemon_ref(),\fR
\fB                         ItemList :: [Item],\fR
\fB                         Item :: ip | port | profile | options,\fR
\fB                         InfoTupleList :: [InfoTuple],\fR
\fB                         InfoTuple :: daemon_info_tuple().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns information about a daemon intended for e.g debugging or logging.

.PP
When the \fIKey\fR is a single \fIItem\fR, the result is a single \fIInfoTuple\fR

.PP
Note that \fIdaemon_info/1\fR and \fIdaemon_info/2\fR returns different types due to compatibility reasons.


.RE
.B
\fBdaemon_replace_options(DaemonRef, NewUserOptions) ->\fR
\fB                                {ok, daemon_ref()} | {error, term()}\fR
\fB                                when\fR
\fB                                    DaemonRef :: daemon_ref(),\fR
